## Review: TASK-004 — EventBus (Internal Async Pub/Sub)

### Quality & Bugs
**No bugs found.** The implementation is clean, correct, and well-structured at 76 lines.

One **design note**: the spec says `asyncio.create_task` (fire-and-forget) but the implementation uses `anyio.create_task_group()` (blocking — `publish()` waits for all handlers to complete). This is actually **better** because:
- Avoids the "coroutine was never awaited" warning seen in executor logs from an earlier attempt
- Works on both asyncio and trio (project convention)
- Ensures handlers complete before returning — no lost tasks
- Testability is much better

This can be revisited if fire-and-forget semantics are needed when integrating with the Application class.

### Implementation Completeness
All checklist items implemented:
- `_Subscription` dataclass with pattern, handler, UUID id
- `subscribe()`, `unsubscribe()`, `publish()`, `_safe_call()`
- `fnmatch` wildcard matching per DESIGN-003
- Error isolation: `except Exception` catches handler errors, logs them, doesn't propagate
- Public exports in `core/__init__.py`

### Test Coverage
32 tests covering all required scenarios:
- Exact match, wildcard match, wildcard no-match, star-matches-all
- Multiple subscribers on same pattern
- Unsubscribe stops delivery, unknown ID is noop
- Handler error isolation (single error, multiple errors, error logging)
- Payload preservation, no-subscriber silent publish
- Public exports verification
- All async tests run on both asyncio and trio backends

### Security
No concerns — pure in-memory pub/sub with no external inputs.

